Drag is one of my favorite forms of performance art, it has been since I saw my first drag show as a college student in Missouri. The variety of skills and the amount of talent it takes to perform drag is awe-inspiring. I’ve always dreamed of getting into it as a performer, myself, and out of all my creative outlets, learning drag has been the most challenging. I have so much respect for the performers who are able to make a career out of drag, they’re some of the most talented and creative people I’ve ever met. #LGBTQIA #drag #dragshow

If you do need to change some things to feel more at peace with your body by setting weight change goals or going through a medical transition, or something else that takes time to achieve: be patient and stay kind to yourself throughout the process. Nothing happens overnight, and you deserve peace and happiness every step of the way. It can be hard to people on social media hitting milestones you want for yourself and haven’t reached yet. Keep in mind, no one is on the same path and you will get there in your own time. And until then, forget about the opinions of strangers and remember that the people who love you see you for who you are, and they also know that you’re so much more than your body. #newyearsresolution #bodyacceptance #bodyneutrality

Photo editing... I’ve taught myself the basics using a few different apps on my iPhone, and it’s a fun and easy way to express my creativity. I can take a quick selfie on my way to dinner, then mess around with it that night before going to sleep, and wake up the next day to a finished product. I love instant gratification, so short bursts of creativity like this bring me a lot of joy. On the other hand, it’s a tool that can be used to change a person’s appearance, unbeknownst to the rest of the world. And if your feed gets oversaturated with images of people looking “better” than they ever could in real life, it can make you start to wonder why you don’t look the same in your own photos. Comparing yourself to others is the main ingredient for developing some major insecurities, and I hate that. So, here’s what I made last night, and the original 🖤🖤🖤 (I love how this looks like it could be my new MySpace profile pic 😝)

Again - there is a ton of grey area here, and I can only cover so much in 90 seconds! Some within the LGBTQIA+ community don’t identify as any of these, and some have their own definitions for what they mean, with a lot more nuance. There’s no rule book on this stuff after all! These are just a few of the terms we have that can be useful when dating and meeting new people to figure out how compatible we might be, but further conversation should always be had with a potential partner in order for a healthy relationship to form 🖤 #lgbtqia #toporbottom

I haven’t posted a selfie like this in a long time. A couple of years ago, every time I went out, I would ask whoever I was with, “can you help me get a cute picture of my outfit first?”
I wouldn’t be able to enjoy myself until after I took a moment to celebrate myself and appreciate the effort I had put into decorating my body for the day, no matter how dressy or casual I was. But after I came out as non-binary and lost so much of my support system, I stopped. I had to rebuild so much of my life and my self esteem, from nothing. For so long, I didn’t know how to feel good about myself or my body, and it was hell. I really missed doing this little ritual of getting a cute picture of my outfit whenever I can. So, I’m entering 2023 committed to loving myself again 🥰 and taking more pictures!

I have moved 5 times in the last 2 years, and I’ve finally found a home I can settle into. I moved into my new home the day before Christmas Eve, so my holidays this year were spent unpacking my past - quite literally - unpacking boxes that have been in storage, full of reminders of the life I lived before. While technically that was my life, I was the one living it - I don’t feel like it truly belonged to me. I had never prioritized myself, my creativity, or my community the way I do now. Life after a divorce is so difficult to adjust to, but I’m finally learning who I am and what I want for myself in a way I never felt like I had the freedom to discover before. I’ve learned that there’s nothing I wouldn’t do to protect my peace, find joy in creativity, and help my community. Those are my priorities this year, and it feels so good to hold that knowledge 🥰🥰
(Swipe for unedited photo)

Wearing a dress, leaning into my feminine side, as a non-binary person… I have feelings about it. Sometimes I get very caught up in my head about whether or not I “look non-binary” enough. Then I remind myself, it’s not what others think of me when they see me that matters, it’s my own opinions about myself!! Do I still feel genderfluid, even when I’m in a dress? Absolutely. And if random strangers don’t see that, I can learn to be ok with that. The people closest to me in my life, who love me, always see me for me, no matter what I’m wearing 🥰🥰 I will never take that for granted. And I will always want to feel cute when I’m out in the city on a Friday night 😝 I hope everyone has as lovely of a weekend as I’m having!! 🖤🖤

For those of you still learning microlabels🖤🖤 Demisexual: a person who needs an emotional bond for attraction to occur. Asexual (ace): a person who either doesn’t feel attraction at all, or might feel it very rarely or in atypical ways. Bottom line is, no matter how a person identifies - if there’s mutual love, respect, and support, between partners, a healthy relationship is always possible 🥰 #lgbtqia #demisexual #asexual

Now that I got your attention! Did you know that over 235 dangerous anti-LGBTQIA laws are currently advancing in different states across the US, most of which specifically target transgender Americans? The ACLU is tracking them on their website, linked in my bio, if you want more information. 
Wanna help? Find your state, get informed, and research your specific state’s legislation and how to fight it. It could be as simple as sending an email! Or if want to really get ✨into it✨ you could to go to a meeting and speak up in person, or organize a fundraiser to help fight back. That would be so hot 🔥
At the very least, you can help by spreading awareness and educating people every chance you get. Trans people have always existed, will always exist, and are nothing to be afraid of.
Happy V day y’all 🍑🍑🍑

Same person, different days.
.
Personal style and self expression is something I spend … a lot … of time thinking about. Who do we get dressed for when we get dressed? Ideally, we dress for ourselves - to make ourselves comfortable, to help ourselves feel happier and more confident when we interact with others. The intricate and sometimes dangerous junction of how others perceive us based on what we’re wearing vs how we perceive ourselves is something trans people experience in a very unique way.
When I look at these 2 pictures, depicting drastically different presentations through clothing and personal style, I see the same person beneath the layers. A multifaceted human, using gender as their own personal playground each and every day. Men’s clothes and women’s clothes are equally appealing to me. Traditionally masculine and traditionally feminine mannerisms and behaviors, equally at my disposal.
Before I came out as genderqueer, womanhood felt like a cage I didn’t know I’d been locked inside of. I spent so much time finding ways to abandon her entirely. But almost 2 years later, I’m learning to embrace ALL the facets of myself and my gender, and feeling more comfortable embracing my feminine side while keeping space for the parts of me that are finally allowed to be something else entirely.
Coming out as genderqueer has been the most freeing thing I’ve ever done, and even though it’s led to countless hardships I’ve had to overcome, I wouldn’t change it for the world. Freedom definitely feels better than all the things I’ve lost along the way anyway. #trans #nonbinary #genderqueer

Binding can also be done with tape specifically meant for use on the skin - but there’s only so much info I can fit into a short form video! Not all trans people bind or even feel the need to, it’s just one of many many options we have available to help us feel more comfortable and confident in our bodies, if we choose to. #trans #nonbinary #binding

I find it odd that people are so afraid of children knowing that trans people exist? Trans kids exist, do people not understand that? From personal experience, if I had known of the existence of just one trans/non-binary person when I was younger, my road to self acceptance would have been a thousand times easier. My life would have been so much happier and more fulfilling. Attempts to block children from the knowledge that we exist only serves to harm trans youth. Kids who are not trans are not going to suddenly become trans just by seeing us in public, that’s not how any of this works. But, they might be more open and accepting of their peers who do happen to be trans. We exist, have always existed, and we’re not going anywhere, no matter how many laws are created against us. #trans #nonbinary #transyouth

Bravery is being afraid, but doing it anyway. But it shouldn’t take bravery to embrace who you are. Someday, something like this won’t take bravery at all - it won’t even be necessary. Someday, we’ll be able to live together in peace, without fear of violence. And I will not rest until I see that dream become a reality not just for me, but for every single other trans person as well. #trans #nonbinary

Let’s be real - these drag bans are just a way to criminalize being trans and we all know it. If you live in one of the many states banning drag, call your representatives. Don’t let them get a moment’s rest until they stop trying to legislate us out of existence. They can pass all the laws they want to but we will always exist and we have a right to exist in public, and to HAVE FUN DOING IT. #trans #dragban

Banning certain forms of self expression … in a country that’s all about life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness? I don’t feel free to pursue happiness if my government wants to dictate what kind of makeup I’m “allowed to wear.” These bills are not about protecting children, they’re about controlling how queer and trans people can express themselves and exist in public. #transrights #dragban

It’s easy to feel hopeless in the face of SO MUCH hate against our community coming from seemingly all sides. I know a lot of people are asking, what can I do to help? What we’re doing right here - talking with each other, supporting each other, brainstorming and getting creative… Organizing. Coming up with ways to shower our community with love and support, and show the rest of the world just what we’re capable of when we stand together. Because the truth is, together, we can be unstoppable. If anyone else wants to join us, send me a DM, the more the merrier 🥰 #trans #love #friendship #advocacy @mikakauffman @trans_entertainment_guild

In the face of this unprecedented amount of anti-LGBTQIA+ laws being introduced & passed across the country, remember that there are more of us, visibly out & proud, than ever before. There are so many young queer & trans people who grew up in a world with representation that Mika and I didn’t have when we were growing up. That makes us stronger as individuals and as a community, and sets us up in a way to heal the damage being done to us now. There’s going to be another side to this, and the future will have so many more trans adults in it 🖤🖤

I get comments every day from people telling me I’m confused or mentally ill. People get into vicious arguments with each other in my comments sections about whether or not trans people deserve the right to live our lives how we choose, while my own life and happiness hangs in the balance. I choose to love myself in spite of it. It is a daily exercise in self empowerment.
.
I came out as genderqueer almost 2 years ago and as a result, I lost family, friends, housing, and almost my own life. I’ve been working hard to gain back all that I lost.
.
Some people equate being trans with being mentally ill, but here’s my truth on that correlation. My mental health was at its absolute worse right after I came out, not because of who I am, but due to the rejection and loneliness I endured as a result of coming out. It was society’s treatment of trans people that affected my mental health negatively, not my gender identity.
.
I’ve been able to rebuild a community for myself, and now not only do I have an abundance of friends I call family, I’ve also grown closer to my parents who have supported me through this. I’ve transitioned socially, while maintaining my public career as a model. I’m making my first plans to transition legally (and I’m getting so excited about seeing an X instead of an F on my IDs!). I was even able to secure stable housing again.
.
Now, my mental health is better than it’s been my entire life, because I did all of that as myself: a strong and confident trans, non-binary, genderqueer person.
.
I got new digitals taken this week and was stunned at what I saw. The amount of work I’ve put into rebuilding my self esteem is paying off!
.
This Trans Day of Visibility, here I am: a trans person who almost lost everything, but will never give up perusing happiness and maintaining their self-esteem.
.
There are as many different ways to be trans as there are trans people, I’m only one of infinite examples of what a trans person can look like. I see someone on a healing journey, comfortable and confident exploring their own gender, all over the spectrum. And having fun while doing it, in spite of those who argue I shouldn’t. #transdayofvisibility #tdov

📢 MOST PEOPLE ARE KIND 📢
It’s so easy to get discouraged and feel hopeless if all you ever see are vicious comments on social media, people debating our very existence or whether it should be “allowed” or not, and politicians calling for our eradication. But every week I’ve been putting myself out there in the real world with a sign saying “Hello, I’m trans!” and most people have been nothing but kind. Remember that 🥰 We’re gonna get through this, together 🖤 @mikakauffman @oliveensemble @thatbroadfromqueens @stefi_grizzy

Dressing professionally as a queer person is something I’ve always struggled with. I used to think “I have to dress the way everyone else is dressing,” to fit in in a professional setting like a casting, but ever since I came out as genderqueer and have decided to fully embrace myself as I am - it’s been getting easier, and today it was even fun! 🥰🥰 I think this was the first time I’ve ever had fun getting dressed for work instead of being filled with anxiety over it. Self acceptance is a powerful tool 🖤 #nonbinary #genderqueer #fashion

Jasmine is like 90 in human years, and had her first trip to the beach yesterday! She’s been to city parks, offices, block parties, bars, so many different homes and hotels, ridden in subways, busses, taxis, and she has even flown ✈️ about a dozen times - but has never seen the shoreline until now. Let her be living proof that you’re never too old to try something new. 🏝 👵🏼

We shared a connection with another human being sharing this planet that might not have otherwise had the opportunity to speak with anyone like us. I believe we absolutely can make this world a little kinder, one conversation at a time. @mikakauffman @stefi_grizzy

Some outtakes from our lengthy conversation with someone who approached us saying, “If you’re out here like this, you must know you might face opposition. Are you ready to defend your perspective?” And, I think we did. I got the feeling this may have been his first time speaking to a trans person face to face, rather than debating ideology online. I believe that by the end of the interaction, he saw us more as individual humans and less as the big scary conglomerate that some media outlets make us out to be. I feel no hatred towards this man, only sadness that while he dealt with personal grief, misinformation took root, and it turned into a misunderstanding of people like us. Love is a superpower, and it wins every time. 🥰 #trans #advocacy @mikakauffman @stefi_grizzy

Religion can be used as a weapon or a tool. The LGBTQIA+ community knows all too well how some people use it as a weapon, but what about the members of our own community who use it as a tool for their own healing & happiness? What about the congregations who chose to use it as a tool to uplift & inspire, the way it’s meant to be used? Religious communities & the LGBTQIA+ community have been pitted against each other for so long, but what about the places where our identities intersect? We might have more in common than we first assume. #queer #nonbinary #religion

I’ve had to take a little break from my beloved AYQB series because I’m organizing a lot of things behind the scenes that have been keeping me busy. But I realized after I made a video talking about my name change, I mentioned “shadow name,” but no one would know what I was talking about 😅 So I made some time to get this video done for y’all, to use as reference for that. Here’s “what is a deadname, and introducing the term shadow name” 🖤
#trans #nonbinary #deadname

Making the decision to publicly change my name, as a model with a 2 decade long career, was one of the scariest things I’ve ever done. I had been going by Jade among family and friends while still using my shadow name at work for almost a year before I made this decision, because I was so afraid of what would happen if I changed it publicly. But, that resulted in a huge decline in my mental health, to the point that I had no choice but to do the scary thing. 6 months later, I’m so happy I did 🥰

Every single person you see in these videos inspires me in a unique way. The one thing I know we have in common, however, is our passion not only for supporting our community at large, but also supporting each other. Not every night is full of love and hugs and positivity. Sometimes, people get pretty rude to us. And every time that happens, we’re there for each other, supporting each other, so we can persevere & continue our fight to make this world a kinder place for all of us.
@austenily @thatbroadfromqueens @mikakauffman @dd44jd @nyc_citywalk @stonewallchuck @thestonewallinn

Individually, we can do great things, but together, we can do even more. Announcing our new organization dedicated to educating others about the LGBTQIA+ community, TQVoices. We’re here, as a resource, for anyone who needs help understanding how to make the members of the LGBTQIA+ community in their lives feel safe, seen, and supported. Send us a DM on Instagram at @tqvoices or an email to transqueervoices@gmail.com if you need our assistance, or would like to collaborate on a visibility or outreach project. We’re here to help 💙💗🤍
@tqvoices @thatbroadfromqueens @mikakauffman

Yes, I cried. Yes, my makeup survived. Because surviving is what I’m best at 😝
I’m so happy I had a friend on set with me today to spend that moment in time with. Thank you @reneecafaro for being you. You inspire me me, you uplift me, you’re a good one 🥰

I met Renee at a fashion week event years ago, and immediately knew - I like this woman. She’s a powerhouse with a background in politics and now works in the fashion industry, with her own luxury plus size clothing line, RCA Public Label. It was a pleasure to be a part of her Pride campaign, where she let us have full creative control over hair, makeup, and styling to shoot her customizable “make it me” moto jackets. I even got to include my “one person pride parade” shirt from one of my friend’s Etsy shops, Sparkletown Studios, and one of my own Stonewall Inn t-shirts. The Human Rights Campaign has issued a state of emergency for members of the LGBTQIA+ community living in the US. It is becoming increasingly scary to be a member of this community and exist in public.
It shouldn’t take bravery to exist, as yourself, in a public space. But right now, we live in a world where it does. Bravery is being afraid, but doing it anyway. Here’s how two of us push past that fear to provide visibility and advocate for our community, so that the next generation of us can live in a world a little bit better than the one we’ve got now.
A lot of y’all are rightfully concerned about our safety as you watch this project each week - I assure you, there’s a great team of people behind the scenes helping to keep us as safe as possible. We definitely couldn’t do this without our loving and supportive allies 🥰 Big thank you to our allies and every other ally in this country showing up in tangible ways to support us through this dark time in history. Your efforts never go unnoticed.

This is the first Pride flag I ever bought, in 2008. I knew I didn’t fit into heteronormative society, but having grown up in a world with zero representation of non-binary people, I was only beginning my long journey to figure out who I’ve always been. This flag hung in many dorm rooms and I’ve worn it in leu of clothing to several Pride parades over the years. It still wears the holes from all those thumb tacks and safety pins like faded lipstick kiss marks from my past self.
Almost 2 years ago, I realized I was non-binary. In the trans community, we have a saying for this, we say “my egg cracked.” I was always a genderqueer person, but that part of myself was locked up inside a shell of outward expectations that had been placed on me by society since I was born. It wasn’t until I got older and learned about all the beautiful ways there are to be a human, that the cracks formed, illuminating something inside me that had actually been there all along. I just hadn’t been given the freedom to open up and see it, because I had spent my life following society’s expectations rather than my own intuition.
When I came out as genderqueer, I faced rejection, isolation, housing insecurity, and subsequently, a mental health crisis - all as a direct result of the way society treats those of us who choose to illuminate the parts of ourselves that go “against the norm,” and to celebrate what we find.
Being told by society that there’s something wrong with you, when you know yourself to be beautiful, is jarring. The correlation between being trans and having poor mental health is entirely because we’re living in a world that actively works against our survival. That’s a heavy burden to carry. I, like many others, carry that weight year-round. But, Pride is our chance to set it down momentarily, to celebrate the radical act it takes to love ourselves in spite of it all, and to celebrate all that our community has overcome in the past, so we can commit to another year of fighting to feel seen, loved, and appreciated, always.
So, Happy Pride weekend to EVERY LETTER IN THE LGBTQIA+! Make time to celebrate who you are and who you love. We all deserve it!!

Because I love seeing everyone’s Pride makeup 🥰 Here’s mine today!
Hot pink and turquoise were actually part of one of the earliest Pride flags, created in 1977 by Gilbert Baker, an artist and openly gay military veteran. These two colors were dropped in 1979, when the gay rights movement took on momentum following the assassination of the first openly gay man elected to public office in California, Harvey Milk. The hot pink dye and fabric was too difficult and costly to acquire at the quantities needed to keep up with demand for the Rainbow Flags, so Baker redesigned the flag to drop the pink, and subsequently removed turquoise as well, to keep a symmetrical design with an even number of colors. So, that’s why I like to pair these 2 colors together in my makeup! Also, they look cool together 😝
Happy Pride Sunday lovies, have fun and stay safe and hydrated out there!! 🖤🖤

Continuing my practice for self-appreciation today, finding selfies I’ve taken over the last year but didn’t post 🥰
Self-love, self-care, and self-appreciation are work. As someone who faced an enormous amount of rejection, loss, and grief after coming out just over 2 years ago, these practices are not easy for me. But I remember a time when they used to be, so I can trust that I’ll get there again. As someone who’s community showed up for me in a major way when I was at the lowest point in my life, I feel a tremendous responsibility to repay that support back into my community, and I never feel like I’m doing enough. Often, I tend to focus so much on my community work, I end up neglecting myself. It’s a trap I’ve fallen into time and time again throughout my healing journey, and it’s one I’m working really hard to avoid. Showing up for myself, loving myself, IS showing up for and loving my community. Thank you to the handful of friends in my life that are holding my hand through this process of finding my way back to that radical self-love I know I’m capable of. Y’all mean the world to me. Also - let’s keep this going - I think it’s working 😝

It’s officially been 2 years since I came out publicly as non-binary 🥰
I lost almost everyone I considered part of my local family here in NYC when I came out privately, so coming out publicly was one of the scariest things I’ve ever done. Two years later, my parents have become my biggest supporters and allies from thousands of miles away, I have a wonderful new chosen family here in the city, and I am full of more love and support than I ever imagined could be possible for me. Big thank you to the handful of friends that stuck by me through this, and to everyone I’ve met along the way that’s been there for me along this journey, I appreciate every single one of you so so much.
And - Happy birthday to my gender 😝🥰

Eccentricity has always come naturally to me, but I spent so much of my life stifling it. I’m so happy I’ve finally given myself the freedom to lean into it 🥰
